n of the state to the role of democracy in its preservation. This study presents the debates between and within contesting Arab ideological trends on a conflict that has shaped, and is certain to continue and shape, one of the most complicated regions in the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArab-Israeli conflict. 0aLiberalismzArab countries. 0aZionismzArab countriesxPublic opinion. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Islamic Studies.2bisacsh  aArab Islamism.  aArab conflict.  aIslamist thought.  aIsrael.  aIsraeli.  aZionism.  aZionist enterprise.  ademocracy.  afreedom.  aliberal thought.  aliberalism.  anormalization.  apeace.  apolitical ideologies.1 aShavit, Uriya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWinter, Ofir, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWinter, Ofir, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packagez978311128282440uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610943940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526109439423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526109439/original  a978-3-11-128282-4  Manchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packageb2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles